1. import pandas as pd
This statement imports the pandas library and gives it the alias pd.
Pandas is used for reading, analyzing, and manipulating datasets.

2. df = pd.read_csv("iris.csv")
read_csv() is used to read the iris.csv file.
The dataset is stored inside a DataFrame named df.

3. print(df.head())
head() displays the first 5 rows of the dataset.
It helps quickly inspect the dataset structure.

4. print(df.tail())
tail() displays the last 5 rows of the dataset.

5. print(df.shape)
shape returns the dimensions of the dataset.
It gives:
(number of rows, number of columns)

Example:
(150, 5)
means:
150 rows and 5 columns.

6. print(df.isnull().sum())
isnull() checks for missing values.
sum() counts the total missing values column-wise.

7. print(df.isnull())
Displays True/False values:
True  -> missing value exists
False -> value exists

8. print(df.describe())
describe() provides statistical summary of numerical columns.

It calculates:
- count
- mean
- standard deviation
- minimum value
- maximum value
- quartiles (25%, 50%, 75%)

9. df.info()
info() displays complete dataset information:
- total rows
- total columns
- data types
- non-null values
- memory usage

10. print(df.columns)
columns returns all column names of the dataset.

11. print(df.index)
index displays row index values of the dataset.

12. print(df.dtypes)
dtypes shows the datatype of every column.

Common datatypes:
float64 -> decimal numbers
object  -> string/text values

13. print(df["Species"].value_counts())
value_counts() counts occurrences of each unique category in the Species column.

Example:
Iris-setosa       50
Iris-versicolor   50
Iris-virginica    50

Meaning:
Each species appears 50 times in the dataset.

Final Conclusion:
This program performs Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on the Iris dataset using pandas.
It helps understand dataset structure, missing values, statistical summary, datatypes, and category distribution.
